<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><a href="https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-BouNuaKEfUI/WHZh3bZBPLI/AAAAAAAALcQ/Z6UJKXRACjohjHO5SKtWJOXYTxKos3A1wCLcB/s1600/AP1110165.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" height="432" src="https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-BouNuaKEfUI/WHZh3bZBPLI/AAAAAAAALcQ/Z6UJKXRACjohjHO5SKtWJOXYTxKos3A1wCLcB/s640/AP1110165.jpg" width="640" /></a></div>Well it was a day of rock and ice split nicely between afternoon and morning sessions. Neither was unfortunately out in the mountains though. The wind was forecast to gust up to 100mph today and with the snow line seemingly retreated to the top of the highest hills Rob and myself didn't feel like we had many other options left for teaching on the final day of the <a href="http://www.expeditionguide.com/wintermountaineering.php">Winter Mountaineering Course</a>. Things did in the event work out OK with Oli, Tom and Russ getting a lot of climbing mileage in on the indoor wall of the Ice Factor as well as becoming quite absorbed in the intricacies of dry tooling at Onich Slab. <br /><div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><a href="https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-5icIMKMpDrY/WHZh4cwg1XI/AAAAAAAALcU/jPJeHqQWWtcgasG-SKT35wd8Iv1G3dD9gCLcB/s1600/AP1110188.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" height="470" src="https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-5icIMKMpDrY/WHZh4cwg1XI/AAAAAAAALcU/jPJeHqQWWtcgasG-SKT35wd8Iv1G3dD9gCLcB/s640/AP1110188.jpg" width="640" /></a></div><br />